,Recommended,286160,10227176,"Posted: 25 May, 2014",all,NightBlader,"Imagine this, you're on Skype with your buddies, when you start saying something like ""I wish we could play board games together"". Yeah, there are sites online with that kind of stuff, but they're kinda lifeless.Yeah, you can buy ""Monopony"" or whatever on Steam, but there's no online multiplayer.With this Early Access simulator game, you can do whatever the hell you feel like, and you just pay once. Plus, if you're looking at this, chances are, you have a Steam account, as well as Steam friends.Just take a quick look at the workshop at the games people put. Monopoly, Cards Against Humanity, Risk, UNO, Scrabble, Candy Land, Sorry!, the list goes on.There are even different themes for games. Nintendo Monopoly, Sonic Monopoly, Mass Effect Go Fish (I'm serious).Being an Early Access game, things are being changed all the time and there's bound to be issues, but even in its current state, it's certainly worth a buy.Is there anything I wish could be changed? Well, yeah, a couple.1. Custom model imports for game pieces.Earlier I mentioned Monopoly. Well, there's no house models, so you have to do like Chess pieces or something in their place. There's also no cats, shoes, cars, or anything. Just standard game pieces. I think adding custom models would make things very neat.2. Adjust the gravity a little for certain objects.I notice when I turn the gravity up, the game pieces move like I want, but then the dice is a little heavy. Maybe there can be sliders for dice, coins, game pieces, and whatever else.3. Tags or Descriptions for game rooms.Yeah, there's the name section, but people put their username or something silly there. Nobody puts what game it is. How about an extra section that lists the game from Workshop currently in use.Like: (Room name) (Host name) (Workshop item name)And if they're using a custom game, just let the user type in the game and that'll show.But even without these, this is simply pure raw fun. Sure, the players have to enforce the rules, but that goes for real board games as well.Recommended for those who have online friends who you really want to play board games with. For 15 bucks, it's worth it."
