,Recommended,286160,13622234,"Posted: 26 December, 2014",all,Polysorbate,"Tabletop Simulator isn't really a game so much as it's... a tabletop simulator.  It has built-in systems for things like automatically stacking, flipping, and hiding cards, and requires players to manually move pieces/tokens/cards/etc rather than relying on a computer to do it ""properly"" as you'd expect in a purpose-built ""Risk"" game or ""Monopoly"" game for example.In this sense it's very much like playing around an physical table with other people; you must actually pay attention to what's going on and understand the rules rather than passively watch the game play itself.  This is both a good thing and a bad thing: on one hand, it makes the game feel much closer to actually playing a board game and it allows you to play by ""house rules"" rather than strictly by the official rulebook.  On the other hand, it necessitates a very complex control scheme which can be a bit overwhelming at first because there are so many different actions that might be needed:- Lift up one card- Lift up a stack of cards- Take one card out of your stock and flip it over- Place a token at a specific location on the board and rotate it properly- Fan out all your cards, flip them over as a group, and allow another player to take one- Move pieces around the board without them bumping into each other- Pick up, shake, and toss (multiple) dice with enough control to prevent them from bumping into anything- Precisely select one thing from among many that are close to each other or on top of each other- Take tokens off a card, flip the card over, and place them back on the card- Place cards in a grid without them getting jumbled together and rotated the wrong direction depending on who's placing the card- Move, rotate, and zoom your view of the game board for a better perspective (like how you might stand up or lean forward to look from another angle in real life)These are just a handful of the interactions that need to be intuitive and seamless, but all the developers have at their disposal is a mouse (2 axes of precise motion, 1 wheel, several buttons) and a keyboard (tons of buttons but they're all on/off, not ideally suited to precise movement).  Actions that would be very simple in real life can require memorization of a different keyboard and/or mouse combinations.  Some things even need to be controlled with buttons and sliders on the screen.  I'm very experienced with games that require a lot of different controls but even I took about 20 minutes or so to fully acclimate to Tabletop Simulator's control scheme.However, all of that said, once you understand the basics of how to control the game it's easy to switch from one game to another since they all use the same control scheme.  Also, many ""simple"" games like Chess or Hearts only require you to memorize a small subset of the full control scheme, so you can get used to things gradually.  Unfortunately I still think the controls will be a barrier to entry for many casual gamers to get into Tabletop Simulator, which is unfortunate since they're probably a big audience for playing tabletop games.Aside from the complex controls, another problem is that some game modules take rather long to load despite having (at times) poor texture quality, which can make small text very difficult to read.With all the negatives out of the way, I still think that Tabletop Simulator is a great idea and it has the potential to become a great product once it's finished.  It needs polish, and it needs more ""standard"" gameplay mechanics to be built-in, such as the ability to snap together hexagonal pieces to form a larger board for example.  Since it's still in development I think it's safe to say the developers are working on these sorts of issues and I eagerly anticipate seeing the finished product.If there was one single thing I'd ask the developers to work on with a high priority, it would be making it possible for cards to be divided into sections by designers, with each section able to be assigned a different texture so that design elements which are common to every card can be reused rather than each card needing to be separately loaded as its own entity.  Along with this they need to make it possible for text to be added to cards via an overlay rather than needing to be baked into the texture.  This would make it possible for text to be sharp and legible without the need for excessively high resolution textures.  This would greatly reduce the amount of texture data that needs to be loaded and greatly reduce system requirements at the same time - it shouldn't take my Haswell i7-based PC over a minute to load a board game.  If these features are already implemented, I haven't seen any Workshop games make use of them for some reason."
