,Recommended,286160,16314627,"Posted: 11 June, 2015",all,Junpei,"Tabletop Simulator is definitely worth the $20 just for Steam Workshop mods. This $20 purchase literally gives you access to tons of board/card games that would normally cost $50 a piece (which you should still buy if you love). On top of tons of licensed board games, you also have a few cool skin swaps (CS:GOopoly, Metal Gear Clue). The way you can actually put your own backgrounds/table images really enhances the mood per game you play. Even without Steam Workshop, you still get chess, checkers, plenty of tabletop assets for role-playing, and more!The main downside to Tabletop Simulator is its interface. Interacting with objects can often lead to frustrating situations. The in-game physics engine doesn't help either. Instead of a game of chess, sometimes it becomes a game of knocking pieces off a table only to realize you forgot to set the object interactions off. Stacking objects also seems to work when it wants to, and more often than not cards will go flying across the table as you attempt to stack them back into a deck. All of these problems increase tenfold when you are playing a game just find and someone enters the game who just wants to♥♥♥♥♥♥around with playing pieces and flip tables (these options can be set to off, thankfully, but it's still tedious). Far too many troll players enter games just to screw around instead of actually play.+ Great Workshop content!+ Surprisingly good value.+ Backgrounds look great, and the option to add custom ones is amazing!+ Tons of assets already come with the game, making setup extremely easy.+ Excellent graphics for the type of program this is.+ Customized table surfaces help when playing/teaching games.+ Creating/joining a server is as easy as can be.+ Plenty of server options to keep trolls from destroying a game (though they still can do some damage unless you lock out EVERYTHING)- Troll players who enter games just to screw around with pieces (not exactly the game game's fault, but it is part of the experience)- Physics system gets in the way of a ton of games, meaning actually playing them is a chore.- Clunky interface/controls that seems as if they could have been implemented better.Conclusion:Tabletop SImulator isn't to be missed. If you can get past a few of its frustrating bits, it's honestly one of the best ways to spend time with friends or complete strangers. Nothing like sitting down at a table and playing a good game of Risk, Monopoly, Formula D, or plenty of other games! If you're even the least bit interested in a board game, look and see if it's on the workshop and try it here before buying (but buy it if you enjoy it, board game devs go through a lot these days). All around one of the best purchases available on steam."
