,Not Recommended,286160,18297944,"Posted: 2 October, 2015",all,elaxter,"AT A GLANCEI can't recommend this sim for anyone unless you fit the niche required to enjoy it.WHAT IS IT?Table Top Simulator is exactly what it sounds like: a simulator of the table. The basic purchase consists of basic game tools such as a 52-deck of cards, chess board and pieces, and majong pieces.This sounds cool in theory, but once you start playing you find that it's more a gimmick than a simulator.WHY?This game is a hassle to use. Loading it up and going through the tutorial gives hopes that the experience will be grand. ""Such possibilities,"" one might think, ""I can play an unlimited amount of table top games with this!"" This is where the game falls short.First, the controls. You control the world with a combination of the mouse and keyboard. You can grab objects and move them around with realtime physics. This sounds awesome, but in practice this is a hassle to move objects around. Because the engine is physics based, all objects need to have physical representation. You can't virtually roll dice without a die being present on the board. To roll said die you have to pick it up, shake it, and drop it, (or right click and click ""roll"") which is a hassle. Playing cards is extremely difficult due to the nature of the physics and stacking, and requires fine control if you want things to go as smooth as possible. Playing a game like Rummy, where all the cards in the discard pile must be seen, takes skill to even begin to play your cards. There are many other issues that exsist, but I must move on.Second, the content. The game starts you with almost nothing in the way of games. No one wants to play blackjack or chess because you can play those games far easier and for free in other places; therefore, you have to either make your own, unique game, or know of a ""non-classic"" table game. (Monopoly, Risk, Cards Against Humanity, Dungeons and Dragons) This requires one of two things: 1) The materials located on the workshop or available as DLC or 2) the ability to model/texture/code objects into the game. The latter is surprisingly easy to impliment if you have the ability to do any of the aforementioned tasks, but seeing as an in-house modeling system is nonexistant in the simulator, you have to rely on out-of-house modeling programs. This is the fence that one is on with this simulator. Either the materials needed to play a game exist as DLC or are found on the workshop, or you have to make them yourself. This is tedious, as you require skill in art to reap the real benefits of this simulator. And since no simplified modeling system exists, it shuts off those without artistic ability from having the real content. You are stuck with other people's items, and if the items for your prefered table game do not exist for download or DLC, you're out of luck.Third, the multiplayer experience is non-existant. This is understandable for this type of simulator, but this simulators ""PUG"" experience is just not there. You have to have a combination of friendship and luck in order to get any enjoyment out of this sim, due to the nature of it. Singleplayer does not exist. Similar to other sandbox games such as Garry's Mod, you have to make your own fun. Only after having a second person (or more!) to play with does this game shine. But forget dropping into a room randomly. The players in there are nonresponsive or unfriendly and either don't know the rules of a game or know the rules too well. Many a times have I tried to host a card game server only to be met with people who had no idea what they were getting into. Many ""I don't know any card games"" and vows of silence.Finally, free alternatives exist. Roll20, a free table top RPG simulator, is free and far more flexible than Table Top Sim. Not only does it stay in 2-Dimentions, (which makes adding content easier) it also features voice and video chat, multiple pages for maps and encounters, virtual dice that don't need to be on the table to use, drag-and-drop support for images so adding maps and tokens is a breeze, a collection of pre-made sprites for use when you have nothing to use, soundcloud support so you can play songs for everyone to hear. All for free, plus an optional membership that can include coding support and vision cones for players. It's far better than Table Top Simulator.FINAL WORDTable Top Simulator is a gimmick, nothing more or less."
