76561198036643645,Not Recommended,286160,29912901,Posted: 13 February,all,Sorryifisuck,"My primary thought while trying to get this to run was ""Wow, this is poorly executed."" And no, I'm not referring to the fact that it was laggy as hell- that's probably because my computer is a potato. My big objection is the basic user interface. I only tried for about an hour before I gave up, and that was an attempt at a Pathfinder game, so my experience is obviosly limited, but the whole UI just seemed awful. For example, the character sheets. In order to enter your class, you don't simply click on a dropdown box and choose the class, nor do you click on a space and type the class name. You first have to actually zoom in and maneuver the screen until you can look at the ""character sheet"" on the screen, and scroll around until  you find the ""Class Level"" line. Then you click edit above that. Then, a little coin appears on the screen, and you right click on the coin. Then you find the space that says ""Class level"" and type in your class name and level- ""Alchemist 1,"" for example- and then you have to click edit again to close that. Then you move on to ""Race,"" and all the other options... There was, so far as I could determine, no way to get a simple, virtual character sheet such as I can get for free on half a dozen websites. It seems like it's so dedicated to creating an illusion that you're actually at a table (an illusion which it fails miserably to create, I might add), that it fails to provide a more user friendly interface, or even the *option* for a user friendly interface.The one positive aspect I did see- the recruiting community was *very* active. If you can stand to deal with this program (and it very well may be better, in games other than Pathfinder), then you're sure to find a game to join."
