,Recommended,286160,15681454,"Posted: 4 May, 2015",all,Casia Games,"OverviewComing back to this after it's full release after coming out of early access I will say that I see this in a completely new light. Tabletop Simulator, unlike other ""Simulator"" titles, is actually a simulator, you get a table and an infinite number of pieces, or at least as many as your computer can handle. The workshop support is fantastic and the amount of games on the workshop alone is enough to justify the price.For PlayersTabletop simulator really is what is says on the tin, it comes with plenty of board games and the option to create your own monstrosity out of the library of both provided pieces and workshop pieces. You do have to have an appreciation for tabletop games but for the base price what you get is more than enough. The DLC games are very high quality and all assets are provided by the game developers themselves if you find one you enjoy don't be afraid to drop a few dollars on it.For Game DevelopersHonestly, for those thinking about board game development or tabletop development this is one of the best tools I could recommend, for the cost of the software you have a way to infinitely create and iterate anything you desire. It's beyond simple to prototype anything you can think of, rpg, board game, card game, etc. Beyond the cost of the software there's no further cost in printing up boards, decks, or buying pieces to prototype your vision with. The support for 3d models, textures, normal maps etc. allows you to set your creations apart from the rest if you're so inclined. If you have a concept in mind Tabletop Simulator can be used to create it within a few hours. The creation tools in my mind come highly recommended.ConclusionI find this title to be good in two aspects, the game play and the game creation. I find more enjoyment with the game creation aspect, spending hours upon hours just creating whatever your heart desires is amazing to me. I would absolutely recommend this if you enjoy tabletop games or are planning on making a tabletop game. It isn't perfect though, the controls can be a little arcane while using keyboard and mouse and sometimes the Vive controls are a little more intuitive, but that's my only problem really, and it just takes some getting used to.Overall: 8.5/10"
