76561198045444719,Recommended,286160,30329883,Posted: 4 March,all,ZedDreppelin,"A nice idea, but like all platforms intended to bring people together to play games, it only works in theory but in reality this is best used by players who already know each and have spent time together playing other games. In other words, if you're expecting to just sit in and join any game, you are sadly mistaken.  Nearly every server for games like Cards Against Humanity, Uno, Clue, Funemployed, Superfight, etc. were private.  No outsiders welcome.  Tabletop Simulator is, in a way, an exclusive club with many rooms and you are prohibited from entering any one of them.  However, when hosting a game, there is nothing in the rules stating you MUST allow anyone to participate in your game.  It does serve a purpose of providing a safe haven for you and your friends to gather and have some fun; but, as I've mentioned before, you will encounter closed private games most of the time.  Yes, you can play single-player, and yes, you can host your own games, but if you don't want to take on the responsibility of being a monitor, what choice do you have?  None, really.  So, if you are part of a group, or have friends who would like to play games together, this is for you.  If not, then I'm afraid your SOL."
